 and order that epitomized earlier classicisms. By identifying elements common to all three arts, and carefully situating classicism within the broader sweep of modernist movements, Ziolkowski presents a refreshingly original view of the cultural life of the 1920s.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aClassicism in artxHistoryy20th century. 0aClassicism in literaturexHistoryy20th century. 0aClassicism in musicxHistoryy20th century. 0aNineteen twenties. 70(DE-601)1041307330(DE-588)4171565-2aNeuklassizismus2gnd 70(DE-601)1046751520(DE-588)4049716-1aRezeption2gnd 70(DE-601)1061050860(DE-588)4068754-5aAntike2gnd 70(DE-601)1062573150(DE-588)4033422-3aKünste2gnd 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  a1920s, era, time period, decade, classic, art, artistic, artist, music, musical, audio, musician, literature, literary, avant garde, movement, genre, modernism, modern, contemporary, 20th century, stravinsky, interdisciplinary, research, academic, scholarly, picasso, ts eliot, poet, painter, composer, wwi, wartime, postwar, world war, themes, forms, culture, cultural, history, historical.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z97831106904390 cprintz978022618398540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226184036423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226184036/original  a978-3-11-069043-9  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles